# Accepted risks — each one is a deliberate cost/benefit call for a public
# demo portfolio with a hard "idle ≈ $0" budget rule (see CLAUDE.md).
# Revisit if any plank starts handling real (non-demo) data.

# (AVD-AWS-0011 retired 2026-07-20: every distribution now carries the shared
# platform-edge-acl web ACL — per-IP rate limiting + AWS managed rules.)

# S3 with SSE-S3 (AES256) instead of a customer-managed KMS key: CMKs cost
# $1/mo each + per-request. Nothing in these buckets is sensitive: public
# site assets, a fictional demo corpus, terraform state (whose bucket is
# created outside terraform with encryption + versioning + public-block).
AVD-AWS-0132

# Unencrypted SNS topics: they carry CloudWatch alarm notifications and
# plank 3's fictional service-request fan-out (no payload secrets).
# Encrypting would require a CMK ($1/mo) because neither CloudWatch nor
# EventBridge can publish through the AWS-managed aws/sns key.
AVD-AWS-0095

# CloudWatch log group without a customer-managed KMS key: it holds Step
# Functions error logs for fictional demo events. AWS-managed encryption is
# on by default; a CMK is $1/mo for nothing sensitive.
AVD-AWS-0017

# Plank 5's dla-etl Athena workgroup deliberately does NOT enforce its
# configuration: Athena rejects CTAS 'external_location' (how the ETL writes
# the curated zone) in enforced workgroups. Only the etl Lambda's role can
# reach this workgroup; the visitor-facing dla-public workgroup IS enforced
# with a per-query scan cutoff.
AVD-AWS-0007

# Plank 4's Fargate task security group allows egress to 0.0.0.0/0:443 — the
# task must reach ECR/S3/CloudWatch Logs public endpoints (the no-NAT,
# no-VPC-endpoint cost pattern), and those services publish no stable CIDR
# narrower than "AWS". Ingress is empty; egress is TCP 443 only.
AVD-AWS-0104

# Plank 4's ECR repo keeps MUTABLE tags on purpose: the demo task definition
# tracks ctr-app:latest so an image rebuild never needs a task-definition
# revision. Only CodeBuild's fenced role can push. Production would pin
# immutable tags/digests — the plank README says so out loud.
AVD-AWS-0031

# Plank 9's web-tier security group admits 443 from 0.0.0.0/0 — it is the
# public tier, and "internet → web :443 reachable" is one of the Reachability
# Analyzer exhibits. Every other tier admits exactly one port from exactly
# one upstream security group.
AVD-AWS-0107

# Plank 9's net-public-web instance carries a public IP on purpose: the
# public-path exhibit. Subnet-level auto-assign stays off; exposure is
# granted per-instance. (Also covers plank 9's SG egress-to-0.0.0.0/0:443 —
# SSM registration + AWS APIs, same acceptance as plank 4's task SG.)
AVD-AWS-0164

# Plank 11's Aurora cluster is encrypted with the AWS-managed aws/rds key
# rather than a customer-managed KMS key: same $1/mo-CMK acceptance as the
# rest of the portfolio (see AVD-AWS-0132), for a scale-to-zero demo cluster
# of fictional data that is destroyed at the end of every demo window.
AVD-AWS-0079

# Plank 9's NACLs allow 0.0.0.0/0 on 443 (public tier ingress) and on the
# ephemeral range 1024-65535. The ephemeral allows are NOT open ingress:
# NACLs are stateless, so return traffic for outbound connections (S3 and
# DynamoDB via gateway endpoints, SSM, the internet-egress probe) must be
# allowed explicitly. Unsolicited SYNs to those ports still die at the
# security groups. All rules are TCP-scoped; RDP is explicitly denied.
AVD-AWS-0105
# AVD-AWS-0102 flags the same NACL rules for their wide port range
# (1024-65535); the stateless return-traffic rationale above covers it.
AVD-AWS-0102
